		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Fave items/books from D&amp;D? :)
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1622755">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Been playing since I was 10 (am now 37.) I have DM'ed mostly, but this thread really sent me back.<br />
<br />
My own favorites, in no particular order:<br />
<br />
The original basic blue boxed set - no explanation needed. I remember picking this up at a Waldenbooks when I was in 4th grade. I still have it (in fairly good condition even!) Sadly I have lost all the dice but one: my original 20-sider. It is so used the points have rounded to the point that when you roll it it takes about a minute to STOP rolling. A friend found me a copy of chainmail, the D&amp;D pre-cursor, but that one I have preserved under lock and key.<br />
<br />
1st edition AD&amp;D DMs guide - the one with the &quot;demon&quot; on the cover. I remember getting strange looks from some of my relatives when they saw it. My mother had to convince them she wasn't secretly the head priestess in a satanic cult with me her devoted disciple.<br />
<br />
Original Tomb of Horrors:  Sphere of Annihilation trap? Yes, please!<br />
<br />
1st edition AD&amp;D PH: My real love affair with Wizards began here. On the rare occasions I am a PC rather than a DM I almost always play a Wizzy. (No surprise why I wound up on this site....)<br />
<br />
Original Ravenloft Boxed Set: Love the setting, hate it, you have to admit the premise was damn cool. I remember running my friends through &quot;Feast of Goblyns&quot; and thinking how cool it was to have them battling in a realm ruled by werewolves and wolfweres.<br />
<br />
From the Ashes Greyhawk boxed set: I love the Realms but Greyhawk was first and I think I've played more campaigns in Oerth than anywhere else. One of my players' favorite campaigns was the redone 2nd edition greyhawk castle.<br />
<br />
The will and the way psionic reference book: The best part about DarkSun in my opinion is the broad incorporation of psionics into the campaign. After Wizards I think Psionics are my personal favorite class. It takes some patience to adjudicate them correctly, but they really spice up a campaign.<br />
<br />
Pools of Radiance computer game: First D&amp;D offficial game I ever played. I loved feeling like I was finally playing D&amp;D on a computer! (my beloved old commodore 64)<br />
<br />
2nd edition complete handbooks: LOVED the fleshing out of character classes and races these books provided, especially the first book on fighters. Took combat from &quot;attack, attack, attack&quot; repetitiveness to called shots, disarms, and ambidextrous fighting styles.<br />
<br />
Encyclopedia Magica:  4 volumes that had (up to that point) EVERY magic item ever released in any D&amp;D book or reference guide. This made individualizing treasure for adventures a breeze.<br />
<br />
Delta Green resource books: I saw Silver's reference to Cthulu above and had to mention this. My favorite adaptation of the Cthulu rules to a specific setting - a modern one! CIA/FBI/NSA agents against Cthulu, oh hell yes!<br />
<br />
4th edition PH/DM: I enjoy the change of pace 4th edition provides with its &quot;MMOized&quot; structure.<br />
<br />
<br />
That of course is just some of the fun stuff I remember. 26 years playing, and I made some of my life-long friends that way (My current group includes men I've been friends with since I was 5, 10, and 13 years old.)<br />
<br />
Thanks for the trip down memory lane Silver. <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" />
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
