			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Fave items/books from D&amp;D? :)
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1622759">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							I used to have a copy of Chainmail, as well. My first ever D&amp;D adventure was as a player in &quot;Keep on the Borderlands&quot;. Within a month I was DM'ing because no one else really wanted to do it.<br />
<br />
My Favorite monster from AD&amp;D days was the Gith. My campaign lasted almost 5 years and was it's primary design was built around Queen 2, side 2. Yes, we played in the &quot;7 Seas of Rhye&quot;. LMAO.<br />
<br />
For a change of place, our group played both the Original Gamma World and Boot Hill.<br />
<br />
Later -- we tried out CoC, and loved it. Delta Green must have been after my time, but it sounds fantastic.<br />
<br />
One summer we played AFTERMATH, which was a far more serious post-apocalyptic game. The rules were amazingly detailed, and we incorporated a ton of extras into our game.  Sikorsky Helicopters, motorcycle mounted jousting, actual blueprints for city and county buildings (back when it was relatively easy to get those kinds of things).<br />
<br />
I gave up gaming for guitar playing, and I gave up school (Physics / Philosophy) for a Guns &amp; Roses lifestyle. If I had it all to do over again, I think I would have stayed in school at that time, and kept gaming.<br />
<br />
Oh, and Arinath: There was a Ravenloft BOXED set? The only thing I remember was a module &quot;Something Something Castle Ravenloft&quot;. We played the hell out of that, as well. <br />
<br />
Oddly enough, since Mindy and I started playing 4E about a month ago (Encounters and Living Forgotten Realms) I made contact with the guy who taught me D&amp;D when I was 9 or 10. Guess what he does for a living? Game designer at Blizzard Entertainment. Small world, eh?<br />
<br />
Edit: Did some digging. This was our Ravenloft: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ravenloft_(module" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ravenloft_(module</a>)
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
