				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Fave items/books from D&amp;D? :)
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1622779">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Hey Lys, the boxed set came after the huge success of the module you linked. Players loved Strahd so much as a villain they made the entire setting based around his area. There were even two later modules released where you go up against him and the lich ruler of an adjacent territory (House of Strahd and Roots of Evil). I just love AD&amp;D worlds with lots of atmosphere, and Ravnenloft has it is spades. Granted, like DarkSun it is a harsh world for players, so I think the DM enjoys things a little too much sometimes (I know I did *insert evil laugh here*) I remember one of my friends wanting to play a Paladin in Ravenloft. I think that lasted about 2 sessions....<br />
<br />
AFTERMATH: GREAT setting. I didn't do much post-apocalyptic stuff but AFTERMATH was great. My group also did some Car Wars for a time (making the failed MMO which came out for a short time a real let-down.)<br />
<br />
One of the great things about the net is the availability of older, hard to find game books via torrent and other file sharing. Every once is a while it is nice to depart from traditional D&amp;D type fare and dive into something different.<br />
<br />
Regarding Delta Green: It really is (IMO) a great setting. You still battle the forces of the Lovecraft's mythos but you do it as a state/federal agent (FBI/CIA/NSA/ATF etc, even armed forces). It is great conspiracy theory/supernatural role-playing. They adapted it a while ago for D20 play but I think I still prefer the traditional D100 CoC rules.<br />
<br />
My latest project is trying to convert the classic &quot;Against the Giants/Queen of the Demonweb Pits&quot; to 4th edition and then taking some suckers (I mean players) through it <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" />
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
