		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Fave items/books from D&amp;D? :)
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1623015">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							For their time: PHB II (3.5e), Complete Warrior/Adventurer/Arcane, and the Magic Item Compendium (As a GM).<br />
<br />
The PHB II introduced some great alternate options that really helped me customize characters (Non-spellcasting paladin FTW.)<br />
<br />
The early Complete X series was a lot of fun. A GM had to get very careful with what they let into a game but the various customization options were great.<br />
<br />
The Magic Item Compendium was a great resource as a GM. It was something a player could get dumb with if you let them pull from without supervision, though. Mostly I loved the quick and easy cost tables in the back so that I could just look over my options with certain wealth levels.<br />
<br />
Recently, the GameMastery Guide from Paizo is great. It's got tables for literally everything you could ever need for on the spot item generation, which is great for me, as I don't really do &quot;random&quot; treasure but I use the tables to get me into the area of specific treasures and then pick appropriate options. It really makes random wand/potion generation FAR FAR easier. Then there's basically a 50 page section of stat blocks for things like &quot;Pirate&quot; and &quot;King&quot; and &quot;Wench&quot;. All the human NPCs you never wanted to stat out and suddenly need stats are there for when your players inevitably jump the railroad tracks and go in a direction you didn't expect.<br />
<br />
The critical hit deck makes critting a whole lot more fun in D&amp;D. The fumble deck is actually somewhat bad for gameplay imo, as I'm not a fan of permanently debilitating players.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer">Quelian Spyralshot<br />
<br />
Reach out and <i>Torch</i> someone.</div></blockquote>
				
                                        
			</div>
			
